<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="market-analysis">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>research</group>
    <domain>market-researcher</domain>
    <summary>Combined methodology: size a market (TAM/SAM/SOM), classify trend timing, map 15-20 named competitors with URLs, and produce a feature-gap matrix from the top 5 competitors with JSON-first outputs.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>market-sizing</tag>
      <tag>competitive-landscape</tag>
      <tag>feature-matrix</tag>
      <tag>tam-sam-som</tag>
      <tag>trend-analysis</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>Market Analysis</title>
    <summary>Market analysis is the combined methodology for sizing a market (TAM/SAM/SOM), classifying trend timing, mapping the competitive landscape (15-20 named players with URLs), and producing a feature-gap matrix from the top 5 competitors. The core rule: run both top-down and bottom-up sizing; if they diverge more than 2x, flag it as a research gap rather than averaging. These four sub-methodologies share data sources and produce JSON-first outputs that feed downstream SDD artifacts.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Desk research without methodology produces TAM theatre (Gartner numbers inflated 3-10x), hallucinated competitors (invented product names), stale pricing (6-18 months behind live pages), and unfalsifiable trend-timing labels ("Early Majority" with no quantitative anchor). Separating the four passes into distinct subagent invocations keeps context windows small, enables JSON validation per pass, and makes the competitive matrix reproducible via competitor snapshots.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Before writing a spec.md for a new product idea — produces SAM number and competitive whitespace</item>
        <item>When the GTM strategist or product manager needs a quantified opportunity ($X M SAM, Y% CAGR, Z named competitors)</item>
        <item>Quarterly competitor refresh: re-scrape pricing pages, changelogs, review sites for moves</item>
        <item>Pre-fundraise: investor decks need a defensible TAM and a feature matrix</item>
        <item>Niche viability scoring inside niche-evaluation flows — replaces guesses with sourced numbers</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Single-customer custom builds with no market</item>
        <item>Pure technical or architecture research — route to pro/dev/software-architect instead</item>
        <item>Ideas fewer than 2 weeks from launch where research will not change the decision</item>
        <item>Highly regulated B2B niches (defense, medical devices) where public data is scarce — use primary expert interviews</item>
        <item>Working business where the decision is growth, not entry — switch to growth-marketer or conversion-optimizer</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="market-sizing">
      <rule>
        <statement>Every TAM number must carry source, year, and geography in the same line. Reject standalone dollar figures with no provenance.</statement>
        <rationale>Top-down numbers from Gartner/Statista are routinely inflated 3-10x. LLMs parrot fabricated CAGRs with high confidence. Citation in the same line is the minimum defense against hallucinated market sizes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Always run sizing top-down AND bottom-up. Flag divergence above 2x as a research gap — do not average or pick the more favorable number.</statement>
        <rationale>Divergence above 2x signals a definitional mismatch, a data quality problem, or a constraint that was not applied consistently. Averaging hides the problem; flagging forces investigation before the number enters a deck or a spec.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>TAM: total revenue if you captured 100% of everyone who could ever buy — the ceiling, not the plan</item>
        <item>SAM: portion of TAM reachable given real constraints (geography, language, industry, company size, tech stack)</item>
        <item>SOM: realistic market share capturable in 3-5 years given budget, brand, and competition</item>
      </list>
      <section name="bottom-up-steps">
        <list>
          <item>Find countable potential customers: LinkedIn search, industry database, platform API</item>
          <item>Estimate the percentage reachable with the current marketing budget and channel mix</item>
          <item>Apply a realistic conversion rate (trial, then paid) from comparable products</item>
          <item>Multiply by price to arrive at Year 1 and Year 3 SOM in dollars</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <section name="sizing-validation">
        <list>
          <item>Can you name 100 specific target companies or individuals? If not, the SAM is not specific enough</item>
          <item>Can you explain the operational path to the SOM? If not, the SOM is aspirational, not a plan</item>
          <item>Does the bottom-up match the top-down within 2x? If not, document the specific constraint causing the gap</item>
        </list>
      </section>
      <reference path="templates/market-sizing.md">Market sizing template with top-down and bottom-up sections</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="trend-pass">
      <list>
        <item>Macro (5-10 years): AI adoption, remote work normalization, demographic aging — use as context, not opportunity</item>
        <item>Industry (2-5 years): no-code tools, creator economy, vertical SaaS — the actionable sweet spot</item>
        <item>Micro (6-24 months): specific tool adoption, API standardization, pricing-model shift — tactical opportunity</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Growth drivers: what accelerates this trend? (technology capability threshold, regulatory mandate, demographic shift)</item>
        <item>Adoption curve position: where in the Rogers curve? — must cite a quantitative anchor, not just a label</item>
        <item>Threats: what could reverse this trend? (competing technology, regulatory reversal, macro downturn)</item>
        <item>Timing verdict: too early (market unaware), just right (market aware + solutions emerging), too late (established winners with moat)</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Require a quantitative anchor for any adoption-stage claim: category revenue at the top 3 players, named buyer logos at recognizable enterprises, or published category spend data. Reject "Early Majority" labels without a quantitative anchor.</statement>
        <rationale>Adoption-stage labels are subjective and unfalsifiable without quantitative evidence. The same trend looks "early" to a bull and "late" to a bear; quantitative anchors resolve the dispute.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/trend-analysis.md">Trend analysis template with drivers, threats, and timing assessment</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="competitor-discovery">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cap the competitor list at 20 named entries with working URLs. Longer lists are hallucination magnets — nobody reads them and the data quality degrades past 20.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents happily produce 40 competitor names when asked for a comprehensive list. Beyond 20, entries are increasingly invented, merged, or mischaracterized. A tight, URL-verified list is more actionable than an exhaustive fiction.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Reject any competitor entry without a working URL. Require URL plus a screenshot or page text as evidence that the product currently exists.</statement>
        <rationale>Web-search agents invent product names, merge two products into one, or cite discontinued products as active competitors. URL verification is the minimum bar for a credible competitive landscape.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Direct: same solution, same problem, same customer — most visible, most cited</item>
        <item>Indirect: different solution, same problem (e.g., Slack vs. Email for team communication)</item>
        <item>Substitute: alternative approach entirely (e.g., outsource vs. software)</item>
        <item>Potential: companies that could enter with their existing capabilities and distribution</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Add a dedicated brainstorm step for substitute and potential competitors before locking the list. Agents routinely miss these two categories without an explicit prompt.</statement>
        <rationale>Substitute and potential competitors drive the most strategic surprises (e.g., Notion entering Evernote's market, Cursor entering Copilot's space). They are invisible to competitive analysis that only scans existing product categories.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <section name="whitespace-identification">
        <rule>
          <statement>Make whitespace claims falsifiable: link to the specific competitor pricing pages and changelogs confirming the gap exists. A whitespace claim without evidence is a hypothesis, not a finding.</statement>
          <rationale>Unfalsifiable whitespace claims drive product decisions based on assumptions that collapse on first customer call. Evidence-backed whitespace survives early customer validation.</rationale>
        </rule>
      </section>
      <reference path="templates/competitive-landscape.md">Competitor landscape table with direct, indirect, and whitespace sections</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="feature-matrix">
      <rule>
        <statement>Snapshot competitor sites before running the feature matrix. The data layer must be reproducible 6 months later — a matrix built from live pages has no baseline to diff against.</statement>
        <rationale>Competitors ship weekly. A feature-matrix assertion from memory or a live page is immediately stale and cannot be audited. Dated snapshots enable the quarterly diff that surfaces actual movement.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Table stakes (Y at all top-5 competitors): required to compete; building these is cost of entry, not differentiation</item>
        <item>Opportunity (Y at 1-2 competitors, N or P at others): candidate for differentiation — validate demand before building</item>
        <item>Validate demand (N at all competitors): may be a gap or may be intentional — check reviews for evidence of demand before claiming whitespace</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Cite at least 5 corroborating reviews or forum posts for every gap declared as an "opportunity." A gap without demand evidence is a hypothesis, not a finding.</statement>
        <rationale>Feature gaps can be intentional (too hard, not profitable, out of scope for the target segment) or unintentional. Review evidence distinguishes between the two and validates that customers actually want the missing feature.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Check G2, Capterra, and Reddit for review text mentioning the missing feature</item>
        <item>Check competitor community forums and roadmap request boards for vote counts</item>
        <item>Check if the gap is listed in any competitor's public roadmap (if so, it may close before you can ship)</item>
        <item>Verify why competitors lack the feature: technical difficulty, low priority, or not aware of demand</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>A feature matrix older than 90 days is decorative — flag and re-run before using in any decision.</statement>
        <rationale>SaaS competitors ship bi-weekly. A 90-day-old matrix has missed 6+ sprint cycles per competitor. Using it for product decisions means building toward a landscape that no longer exists.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <reference path="templates/feature-matrix.md">Feature matrix and gap validation templates</reference>
      <reference path="templates/competitors-snapshot.sh">Script that freezes competitor URLs as dated markdown snapshots</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Running only top-down sizing without a bottom-up cross-check</description>
        <reason>Top-down numbers from analyst reports are the ceiling, not the plan. Without a bottom-up check, the SOM is detached from operational reality and cannot be defended to investors or the team.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Feature-matrix based on live pages without a snapshot</description>
        <reason>A live-page feature matrix cannot be reproduced 6 months later, cannot be diffed to show competitive movement, and is immediately stale as competitors ship.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Declaring whitespace without review-site evidence of buyer demand</description>
        <reason>Feature gaps can be intentional. Without buyer demand evidence, a whitespace claim leads to building features nobody needs while ignoring the actual gaps buyers care about.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Using a competitor list that omits indirect and substitute competitors</description>
        <reason>Indirect and substitute competitors are the most common source of disruption. A list of only direct competitors produces a false sense of the competitive moat.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent conflates "market size" (revenue) with "user count" and reports them interchangeably</description>
        <reason>SAM in dollars and SAM in seats are different artifacts with different implications for pricing and GTM. Always demand explicit units in every market-size assertion.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent cites CAGR with two decimal places without a source</description>
        <reason>Treat any CAGR more precise than the nearest 5% as fabricated unless it has a source URL and a page number. Real analyst reports round to one decimal place; invented numbers have false precision.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent silently truncates pricing tables from long SaaS landing pages</description>
        <reason>Web-fetch tools cut off page content; pricing tables at the bottom of long pages are omitted. Pass --only-main-content and verify that the output includes the full pricing section.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent cites Gartner or Forrester reports it cannot access because they are paywalled</description>
        <reason>An agent that cannot access a source will sometimes return a confident summary anyway. Require a public URL or mark the source as "(source unverified)"; never accept a paywalled citation without the original text.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent's feature-matrix pass degrades after 10 competitors in long context</description>
        <reason>Chunk the matrix to 5 competitors per invocation and merge the JSON. Long-context degradation causes missed features and incorrect Y/N/P assignments past the 10-competitor mark.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent marks a single-channel SAM as "100% reachable" without a CAC ceiling</description>
        <reason>Every channel has a ceiling — the total reachable accounts via that channel at a given CAC. Without a ceiling, the GTM plan exceeds the actual addressable population.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/market-sizing.md" purpose="TAM/SAM/SOM sizing template with top-down and bottom-up sections"/>
      <template path="templates/trend-analysis.md" purpose="Trend analysis template with drivers, threats, and timing assessment"/>
      <template path="templates/competitive-landscape.md" purpose="Competitor landscape table with direct, indirect, and whitespace sections"/>
      <template path="templates/feature-matrix.md" purpose="Feature matrix and gap validation templates"/>
      <template path="templates/competitors-snapshot.sh" purpose="Bash script that freezes a competitor URL set into a dated snapshot folder via firecrawl"/>
    </templates>
  </content>
</methodology>
